Just as the beauty of a crafted work clearly indicates the beauty of its craft; and the beauty of crafting indicates the beauty of the title of mastery derived from that art; and the beauty of the title of artistry in the master of a workman indicates the beauty of the attribute of that artist pertaining to that art; and the beauty of his attribute indicates the beauty of his talent and aptitude; and the beauty of his talent indicates the beauty of his spirit, essence, and reality; so too does the beauty and beauty in all the beautiful creatures of this universe, from beginning to end, and in all beautifully made works, bear definitive witness to the beauty and beauty of the actions of the All-Glorious Artist.  And the beauty and beauty of His actions undoubtedly point to the beauty and beauty of the titles, that is, the names, that bear witness to those actions. And the beauty and beauty of the names definitively testify to the beauty and beauty of the sacred attributes, which are the source of the names. And the beauty and beauty of the attributes definitively testify to the beauty and beauty of the essential attributes, which are the source of the attributes.  And the beauty and beauty of the essence of His essence, which is active, identified, and manifest, bears witness with undeniable certainty to the beauty and beauty of His essence, the sacred perfection of His essence, and the sacred beauty of His reality. That is to say, the All-Glorious Maker possesses such boundless beauty and beauty, befitting His sacred essence, that a single shadow of it beautifies all beings from beginning to end. And He possesses such pure and sacred beauty that a single manifestation of it has freely adorned the universe. And He has adorned and illuminated all spheres of existence with flashes of beauty and beauty.  Yes, just as a work cannot be without an act, so too can an act not be without an agent. And just as it is impossible for names to be without names, it is impossible for attributes to be without attributes. Since the existence of an art or a work clearly indicates the act of the one who performs that work, the existence of that act also indicates the existence of its agent, its title, and the attribute and name that constitute the work.  Of course, the perfection and beauty of a work also point, with certitude and obvious certainty, to the perfection and beauty of the act itself, which in turn points to the beauty of the name appropriate to it, which in turn points to the beauty worthy of the attribute, which in turn points to the beauty of the ability appropriate to that ability, which in turn points to the perfection and beauty of the essence and reality worthy of and compatible with the essence and reality. Similarly, just as it is impossible for the perpetual activity beneath the veil of these works to be agentless, so it is by no means possible for even the names whose manifestations and inscriptions are visible to the eye on this creation to be without attributes;  And since it is impossible for attributes such as power and will, which are felt at the level of observation, to be without a purpose, all the works, creatures, and artefacts in this universe, with their innumerable existences, definitively point to the existence of the Creator, the Maker and the actions of their agents, the existence of their names, the existence of their attributes, the existence of their essence, and the necessity of the existence of the sacred essence, so too, the various perfections, distinct beauties and various beauties seen in all of those artefacts point to the existence of the actions, names and attributes of the All-Glorious Maker.  and they testify most clearly and decisively to the infinite perfections and infinite beauties of their beings and their beings, which are unique to them, worthy of them, and in accordance with their necessary and sacred nature, and to their beauties, each exceeding the entire universe in their own right. Hello, I a 17-year-old girl from Ethiopia reaching out for help. I was a dedicated student in 11th grade, excelling especially in Math, but I had to stop learning because my family could no longer afford it, and we often go without food. My current situation is incredibly difficult. My mother is ill and unable to work, my father is going crazy and now lives on the streets, and my younger brother risks being unable to take his final exam if we don't pay his school fees. He is also bullied for our old clothes, which breaks my heart. The stress of our situation has become so overwhelming that, at times, I've felt hopeless and even considered ending my life, but I knew I could never do that to my mother and brother. Growing up, we experienced happiness before my father began struggling with alcoholism and drug use, leading to difficult times. Now, our family faces significant hardship, and my mother's family constantly bullies us. I don't want to see my mother crying anymore, and I feel lost and don't know what to do. It's as if fate itself is against us, and I'm so tired of this life. I dream of working to support my family, of giving my brother a better life, and of becoming an actress or a law student, but I don't know where to start. I don't have anybody I can ask for money, and I'm desperate for help. It feels like no one wants to help me, and I don't know what I'm trying for anymore. Please, someone, anyone, if you care at all, please help me. I don't know what to do.

So there's this lore between "Can't Feel My Face", "Tell Your Friends", "The Hills", and "Starboy". I'd like to explain it time-wise The Hills: The Weeknd crashes the car probably indicating he had no hope in life. Then he walks to his home, to find out there's a red headed man/the devil, and wants to strike a deal.  Cant Feel My Face: The Weeknd ends up at a bar, nobody really likes him, until the devil shows up, and throws a lighter at him. This is the deal being done by the devil from The Hills, and this means that The Weeknd has sold his soul for fame.  Tell Your Freinds: It starts off with a bush, probably indicating that The Weeknd has prayed to God, wanting to be forgived. Then he buries his old self (the one who striked a deal with the devil for fame), and walks away. It turns out the devil was following him, and then The Weeknd shoots him. Indicating that the devil is finally gone.  Starboy: finally, after getting rid of the devil, he gets rid of his signature haircut, and kills his old self. The Weeknd ended up destroying his accomplishments by using the cross so that the devil wont come after him. After everything, he drives away, hoping for a new life.

My almost 19 year old son, and 18 year old daughter, are both going thru this very thing right now. My son has dating the neighbor girl about a thre-quarter mile down the road since they were about 13-4, ever since he took her their 8th grade dance. My daughter started dating a nice young man who lived in town who she had homeroom with her Freshman year. First relationships, first kisses, first feelings, etc for them both. They have both been moping around for the last week feeling pretty down and trying to figure it out. They both feel "trapped" in the situation, since they ALL share the same friends, since grade school, all know the same people, go to the same places, etc. And everyone also knows everyone's business and all of the details of the breakups. Its by no means easy, whether you are 18 or 19, 25 or 30, or 45 or 50, to break up in a small town.
